    "summary": "The Phrygian Kingdom (c. 1200–700 BC at its peak) was a major Anatolian power centered in central Turkey that dominated much of the peninsula after the collapse of the Hittite Empire, with its capital at Gordion. The Phrygians were an Indo-European people who had migrated into Anatolia from the Balkans around 1200 BC in the same migrations that destroyed the Bronze Age civilizations. Their culture blended Anatolian traditions with influences from neighboring peoples.\n\nGordion was a sophisticated urban center with elaborate 'Phrygian' stone sculpture, distinctive geometric pottery, and evidence of advanced woodworking technology — the wooden tomb furniture preserved in elite burial mounds (tumuli) at Gordion represents some of the finest ancient woodcraft ever found. The Phrygian king Midas (see [[event:1952|King Midas Historical]]) is the most famous Phrygian ruler. The kingdom was devastated by the Cimmerian invasions around 696–695 BC, which destroyed Gordion and effectively ended Phrygian political power. Phrygian culture persisted, however, and the 'Phrygian cap' became a symbol of the east in Greek art and later of liberty in the French Revolution.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phrygia",
